## What Makes Oval Diamond Eternity Rings Different

A full oval diamond eternity ring is a fundamentally different product from a round eternity ring. To set ovals continuously around a shank, Blue Nile sources matched sets of 8–14 stones that are identical in length, width, depth, color, and clarity. The oval cut's elongated silhouette makes this sourcing harder than for rounds: two ovals with identical carat weight can have different dimensions, different face-up shapes, and different apparent sizes. Matched-set sourcing for oval eternity rings takes longer and costs more than matched rounds.

The production consequence: natural oval eternity rings are graded H-I/SI1-SI2, and lab-grown oval eternity rings are graded F-G/VS2-SI1. At individual stone sizes of 0.15–0.5ct in a 2–4ct total-weight ring, SI1-SI2 inclusions are not visible to the naked eye. This is the universal industry standard for matched oval sets — not a quality compromise. See the [oval diamond wedding band guide](/oval-diamond-wedding-band) for the full explanation of why matched sets require this specification.

The oval cut's size-per-carat advantage carries into eternity rings. A 2ct oval diamond eternity band covers more visible finger surface than a 2ct round eternity ring because each oval's elongated shape spans more width. The same size advantage that makes oval engagement rings appear larger than rounds applies to every stone in the eternity band — buyers get more apparent coverage per dollar. For the complete oval size-per-carat analysis, see the [oval cut diamond guide](/oval-cut-diamond).

Oval diamond eternity rings cannot be resized. The diamonds run all the way around the shank, leaving no plain metal to cut or expand. Confirm your ring size before purchasing. If your size is not settled, a half-eternity (seven-stone) oval band is the correct choice — those have a plain lower shank and can be resized.

