The inflection sits between 2ct and 3ct. At 2ct, $124 is a rounding error — choosing natural is defensible as a personal preference for mined origin. At 3ct, paying $906 more delivers H-I/SI1-SI2 instead of the lab's F-G/VS2-SI1: more money for lower clarity. By 5ct, the premium exceeds the lab ring's entire price. By 8ct, it is $23,427.

The only counterargument: resale. Natural oval eternity rings retain value on the secondary diamond market; lab-grown do not. If you plan to sell within 10 years, natural above the inflection point may recover more at resale. For rings worn as daily jewelry and kept, the resale argument is irrelevant — lab is the rational choice above 2ct.

> **Farzana's take:** "The inflection point is the first thing I show a client who asks about natural eternity above 3ct. At 2ct, I genuinely can't tell the difference between natural and lab sitting next to each other. At 5ct, I still can't tell the difference — but the natural costs $6,586 more for lower clarity grading. For a diamond eternity band oval diamonds that you're wearing daily, those savings buy a second ring or a stone upgrade on the engagement ring itself."
>
> — *Farzana Hasan, Diamond Specialist, DiamondCritics*

